         <div type="entry">
                <head>Leon of Ḥarran</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Leon-of-Harran</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/337</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">328</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="247"/>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/596</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">Melkite theologian and <foreign rend="italic" xml:lang="en-x-gedsh">synkellos</foreign> to the <abbr>bp.</abbr> of Ḥarran in the
                        late 8th or early 9th <abbr>cent.</abbr>
                        <note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">(late 8th or early 9th <abbr>cent.</abbr>) [<abbr>Melk.</abbr>]</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>Melkite theologian and <hi rend="italic">synkellos</hi> to the <abbr>bp.</abbr> of <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Harran">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/216">Ḥarran</placeName>
                        </ref>
                        in the late 8th or early 9th <abbr>cent.</abbr> Leon was a disciple of Giwargi of
                        Maypherqaṭ (Martyropolis) and, like his teacher, advocated a Chalcedonian
                        christology. He authored a Letter to his friend <abbr>Bp. </abbr>
                        <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Eliya-late-8thearly-9th-cent">Eliya</ref>, with whom he had discussed christological matters
                        previously in Ḥarran. This Letter is known only through Eliya’s reply, which
                        preserves several fragments. In the Letter, Leon requests Eliya to make
                        known his reasons for converting from a Chalcedonian to a miaphysite
                        christology. He outlines his own theological position and poses several
                        specific christological questions, to which Eliya responds.</p>
                </div>
